ut war as it is seen, lived and interpreted by women who were citizens of the former Yugoslavia. Many of the accounts portray the horrific experiences the victims had to face and the book addresses issues of sexual, physical and psychological violence, as well as problems of confinement, upheaval and family separation. In a completely new insight the book dispels the myth that many of the women were peasants, and shows that in fact they were educated, middle-class women with independent careers. The study also depicts how some of the victims attempt to come to terms with the aftermath of wartime abuse. This probing, accurate and unique investigation of victimization is an unparalleled volume that presents a completely new perspective maintaining that violence against women in war is not independent of peace-time victimization and the imbalance of power between sexes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh  aPersonal narratives, Bosnia.1 aBlagojevic, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKonstantinovic-Vilic, Slobodanka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKonstantinovie-Vilic, Slobodanka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMrvic-Petrovic, Natasa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNikolic-Ristanovic, Vesna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNikolić-Ristanović, Vesna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStevanovic, Ivana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978963386549140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978963386